text: A comment section filled with foolish Shymalan haters. Allow me to share a revelation I've had while looking at his movies and reactions. Neither, he the writing or acting is the problem, YOU are. You were so blown away by the twist of the Sixth Sense that all you wanted to see out of him was the twist in his later movies, so you ignored the plots of his later movies and thus when something happened you did not like you called it a twist and hated the movie, and then condemned him for it.  After watching his stuff, I have come to the conclusion that his movies are far too smart for their audiences. These days, audiences don't watch movies to learn or be inspired, they just want everything spoonfeed to them. Audiences today are like evil deities, they expect something to go their way and whenever some comes that challenges them they retaliate. Your always asking for something new, so when something "new" comes out you enjoy it, and almost immediately afterwords hate it and call it cliche. The truth is, there are only so many stories that can be told and have been told for thousands of years. So what if something has been done before? I want to see how it will be executed here.  I suggest you people rethink the way you look at movies and come to the sad fact that you have to give yourself to a movie, an movie does not give itself to you. And two more things, the plot twist of The Sixth Sense has been done before, and Avatar The Last Airbender was nothing but an attempt to make money off the success of Anime in America and is not really that good. I'm watching the cartoon right now, and I am profoundly disappointed in it.

text: So there are two ways to see this film:  1.M Night Shyamalan, the failed director behind such notorious stinkers like The Last Airbender and After Earth, is teaming up with the producers of cheap Z grade throwaway horror movies, to make a cheap little horror flick in the tired and lame "found footage" genre. OR 2.M Night Shyamalan, the genius director behind The Sixth Sense and Unbreakable, after being constrained by big budget studio films and enduring a fall in critical approval, is returning to smaller budgets to return to his roots and make something more pure, honest and artistic on a smaller scale. (with oversight from the producers of smash horror hits to make sure he doesn't go off course)   Which one do you chose? My guts tells me its the 1st, but I hope as a huge fan of Sixth Sense and Unbreakable that its the 2nd.

text: This movie was just really bad- warning my comment is pretty spoiler-y like boring  wasn't scary but didn't have enough going on so it could be funny. Like the "horror" was funny but there was hardly any of it and the characters so unappealing I honestly didn't care if they made it through or not. And did they just forget about the germaphobe plot point for 90 percent of the movie bc i'm pretty sure people who are afraid of germs don't just lie down on the floor and in the dirt and flush the toilet with their hand as opposed to the foot. Also how do the kids not have ptsd after murdering two people and having shit rubbed in their face. And they implied the daughter went back and EDITED THE FOOTAGE of her murdering someone. What the fuck. Then they rap about it like nothing fucking happened!? Plus the art choice with the font to show what day it was oh my god how awful- like couldn't have used a calendar or something? not MONDAY NIGHT big red letters scary sounds jfc idk if that was supposed to be a "child's editing" but it was bad either way. Plus delivery of exposition through interviews in the kids "documentary" is the laziest, most forced thing i've ever seen. Also the kid who played the brother in the movie, during the flashback with their dad, had brown eyes, not blue, so there's that too. Also this movie's half-assed excuse with mental illness to blame for the state of the "grandparents" not only is really harmful to anyone who isn't neurotypical, but is so half-assed and poorly researched that it makes me sick. The kids not having any signs of post trauma stress disorder, and even fucking singing about what happened just makes things so much worse. Like it was an attempt at comedy but just came off extremely forced and brought up more plot holes. Like HOW DO THEY NOT HAVE PTSD OR ANY SIGNS OF TRAUMA AFTER BRUTALLY MURDERING TWO PEOPLE. It just pisses me off ?? Also the kid didn't have any shit on his face in shots immediately after the whole incident happened which was like ok. Don't go see if you think it looks funny, or scary, bc its very little of either. Boring filler, its not suspenseful, its just...bad...even someone who is terrified of horror movies went with me and agreed. When is a good horror/thriller film going to come out?

text: You no what I don't get? All the critics are giving this movie a 6/10 while the rest of the Internet is like "OMG best movie ever M. Nights revival!" I personally loved it. And M. Nights amazing skills at being amazing has made the found footage aspect FLAWLESS. I can't remember a single time the found footage aspect felt unnatural or forced. I also like the way the grandparents were delivered. The main characters had never met them forehand, which helped drive forward the creepiness of living with a stranger. The grandparents always felt off throughout the movie. Something was wrong VERY wrong with the whole situation, but you couldn't put your finger on it until the mandatory M. Night plot twist. Also, the acting was really good. OMG NANA WAS SO SINCERE WITH EVERYTHING SHE SAID UGH. There was one pretty bad thing though. There was a obvious plot hole. You probably know what I'm talking about if you've seen the movie, but I'm not going to say it strait forward. Word limit bye.

text: I've already seen this movie, and I don't recommend it because is more comedy than terror or even suspense, but a disgusting comedy. If you want to expect the oven scene with those pain shouts from the girl, sorry for you to hear this, because it was replaced with the old man rubbing a shity diaper over the kid's face. Yeah, "terror". Seriously? The trama was quite good, but the characters fucked it all, with 'depresion times' and 'I-don't-have-a-fucking-idea-what's-going-right-now' moments. I expected more on this movie, but is actually the same crappy "horror" movie of nowadays, with a few screamers but with more 'toilet humor' (even I question myself, why some people likes that type of "comedy"). Even the scene where the girl (that was a pain in the ass) frightens his bro is scarier than the other scenes of the movie. There where moments where I wanted to get up, say "You know, fuck it all" and go for a refund because this movie was, is and ever will be the same bullshit with themes poorly explained and stupid characters that are like "Oh yeah, we just recorded how our "grandma" was naked while she was scratching the fucking door with her nails in midnight, and how our "grandpa" tried to kill somebody and having allucinations because he have schizophrenia, but everything is good because that's why they're old and they make us cookies, yaaay~". Why the the stupidest characters always survive?

text: The kids go over their grandparents house for a week because they never met their grandparents. Their mother left when she was about 19 because she got into a huge fight with them that turned physical with them slapping each other. She ran off with this guy who she had kids with. The dad left when the boy was about 8 and the girl was 10 all because the boy lost a school football game. The kids meets the grandparents and they're pretty fucking strange. The grandpa shits himself and burns his diapers and is paranoid to the point of attacking strangers in public and also seems to have suicidal thoughts. The grandma also has weird episodes at night where she pukes, scratches the wall, and even walks around the house at night. The girl tries to interview the grandma about the day her mom left twice causing the grandma to freak the fuck out. Also, this other girl keeps stopping by to check on the grandparents because they both volunteer at some mental institute and haven't been showing up for a few days. It is revealed the main girl is insecure about her looks and does not look in the mirror, this does not affect the plot in any real way though... One night, the children are talking to their mom and tell her that they are really freaked out about their grandparents behaviour. The kids show the mom the grandparents on camera and it turns out they aren't really the grandparents and they have been staying with complete strangers for a week in their real grandparents home. These people seem to have escaped from the mental hospital, they murdered the real grandparents (the girl finds their bodies) and have been living their ever since. One night while playing a board game the couple go bat shit crazy. The old dude rubs shit from his diaper on the boys face. They also discover the women who kept coming got hung from a tree. The old women attacks the girl in which she takes some glass and stabs the old bitch to death. The boy slams the old guys head in a refrigerator. The cops arrive and save the kids. There assholes, I spoiled the plot. The movie sucked ass though. So... go fuck yourselves. Good night every body! ðŸ˜€

text: I just finished watching the movie then, and I'm still laughing at some of the scenes. The movie is quite good, so by no means am I saying that it's bad or anything like that. And I'm also not talking about the bits in the movie that were purposely comedic, I'm talking about the Grandma. The way that character behaves, given the physical appearance of the women, had me almost crying with laughter everytime she flipped out and done weird schizophrenic shit. Theres a scene where she runs from side to side in the hallway with her head down and arms backwards, charging like a bull, and it is one of the funniest things I've ever seen. The rest of the characters, however, can be taken seriously, and the plot is pretty good too, along with the plot twist. So I still recommend this movie, but mainly because you'll get such a good laugh watching the scenes with the Grandma.
author: Kurt Bauer

text: Just watched it. Was pretty lame. It has the typical lazy movie development they use for horror movies nowadays (random family moments between "shock" scenes that start off with a weird happening and then increase in weirdness until it is supposed to be scary. watch paranormal activity and youll see what i mean (even though this one is much better than paranormal absurdity)). The plot is easy as fuck. The twist too (and it adds nothing new to the plot. lets call it a "surprise" rather than a "twist"). The movie in general is entertaining and watchable, but then the ending is pretty stupid: grandpa playing with shit to gross viewers out for no reason and grandma following the girls camera in... a strange way (i still dont get that scene. why the fuck was the girl moving the camera left and right slowy??? Just to show grandma can take a step right each time???). The mum's interpretation is the best thing in the movie. But whats that scene at the end? We dont care whyÂ the mumÂ didnt talk toÂ her parents because you guys havent developed the story in that direction! You kept our attention focused on what the fuck was going on with the grandparents!!! The ending scene looks like it belongs to a different and better film, and it definetely doesnt belong in this one... (im talking about the mum talking to the camera, not about the boy rapping)

text: To me, the scares in this movie were set up quite well, because they did a great job emphasizing the sheer unpredictability of the grandma and hence played on our fear of the unknown. It kept me on edge for much of the movie, as I never knew what the grandma would do next. Even though "The Visit" may not have been a great movie, I personally rank it higher than a lot of ghost movies (even including "The Conjuring" and "Lights out") in terms of scares.

text: I feel the essence of horror in this film is so subtle, so mysterious, and so so very curious.  I don't know when I have to close my eyes. Everything is slow but creepy.  Starting from his grandmother who was "sick" every night, grandfather who likes to wear party costumes (and attack other people suddenly), and many more.  There are some parts that, wooh ... I feel I don't need to watch it. So I decided to press play (always after the pause button). Haha.  If I were them, I might not have stayed 7 days.  In my opinion, this movie is more thriller-horror huh? Compared to just horror.  I have a few questions for all of you who have watched this film.  -What did Becca find after she reached the basement?  - Did their fake grandmother and grandfather put them in the pool?  -So, their daughter, Claire, they put in the pool too? Are they mental patients?  - What happened at the end to their fake grandmother and grandfather?  I need an answer. Thank you very much.
